Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), including user ratings and revenue. ● Certain columns, like ‘cast’ and ‘genres’, contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. ● There are some odd characters in the ‘cast’ column. Don’t worry about cleaning them. You can leave them as is. ● The final two columns ending with “_adj” show the budget and revenue of the associated movie in terms of 2010 dollars, accounting for inflation over time

  1. Which movie has the highest revenue?
  2. Which movie has a the lowest revenue?
  3. Look at which genre gave the most revenue?
  4. Which Genre is the most Popular?
  5. What is the relationship between budget and revenue?
  6. What is the relationship between popularity and runtime?
  7. Does a larger budget lead to larger revenues?
  8. What is the relationshp between votes and popularity?
  9. What is the relationship between budget and runtime?
  10. Do all movies make profits?
  11. Which genre is the most common?
  12. Which Director has directed the most movies in the list?
  13. Which director has the highest earning movies?
  14. Which production company produced the most movies?
  15. Which production company had the highest revenue?

In [22]:
# Create a Container Dictionary
averages = {}

# Split the data into different regions
for genre in df_movies['genres'].unique():
    df_genres = df_movies[df_movies['genres'] == genre]

    # Apply an aggregation function
    average = df_genres['revenue'].mean()

    # Combine the data into a DataFrame
    averages[genre] = [average]

aggregate_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(averages, orient='index', columns=['Average_Revenue'])
aggregate_df.head()

5. What is the relationship between budget and revenue?¶

In [29]:
def scatter_chart(column1,column2,x_label,y_label,graph_heading):
    
    x=df_movies[column1]
    y=df_movies[column2]
    plt.scatter(x,y)
    #calculate equation for trendline
    z = np.polyfit(x, y, 1)
    p = np.poly1d(z)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.title(graph_heading)
    plt.grid(True)
    #add trendline to plot
    plt.plot(x, p(x),color="red")
In [30]:
scatter_chart("budget","revenue","budget","revenue","Graph showing Relationship between Budget vs Revenue")

Observation:
From the graph we see that the scatterplot is quite close. There seems to be a positive relationship between the variables. This shows that here is a some correlation between budget and revenue.

13. Which director has the highest earning movies?¶

In [43]:
#calculate the total revenue for the films directed by the director
def barh_plot(column1,column2,sort_column,drop_unknown,title,x_label,y_label):
    director_revenue = df_movies.groupby(column1)[column2].sum()
    director_revenue=pd.DataFrame(director_revenue)
    director_revenue=director_revenue.sort_values(sort_column,ascending=False)
    director_revenue.drop(director_revenue[director_revenue[drop_unknown]==0].index,inplace=True)
    director_revenue.head(20).plot.barh()
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)
    plt.grid()
In [44]:
barh_plot('director','revenue',"revenue","revenue","Top 20 Directors who generated the Highet Revenue","Revenue","Director")

Observation:
From the graph we see the top 20 directors with the highest revenue . Steven Speilberg has the highest revenuet and RSam Mendes the least.

Conclusions¶

  1. Avatar has the highest revenue at 2781505847.
  2. 6016 movies did not make any revenue
  3. Crime|Drama|Mystery|Thriller|Action genre has the highest revenue
  4. Crime|Drama|Mystery|Thriller|Action genre is the most popular
  5. Movies that have a high revenue tend to have a higher budget.They are also more popular.
  6. There is a strong positive relationship between popularity and runtime.
  7. Movies that have a high revenue tend to have a higher budget
  8. There is a strong correlation between popularity and runtime
  9. There is a strong, positive relationship between budget and runtime.
  10. It is clear from the graph that the revenue is generally much higher than the budget over the years.
  11. Drama is the most common genre
  12. Woody Allen directed that most movies with a total of 45.
  13. Steven Spielberg has the highest revenue films.
  14. Paramount pictures produced the most movies.
  15. Paramount pictures has the highest revenue. We can also see that the number of production companies has increaseed of the years.

Limitations¶

  1. The dataset contained rows with missing data. This data was filed with unknown.
  2. There was 1 row of duplicated data that had to be removed.
  3. There were a large number of unknwon production comapnies, this may limit the accuracy of which production company produced the most movies and which company had the highest revenue. The unknowns had to be removed.
